 from China, Greece, and biblical antiquity to the European Renaissance and nineteenth century-encompass sweeping and urgent programs of thought. Constructed as literary fragments, aphorisms open new lines of inquiry and horizons of interpretation. In this way, aphorisms have functioned as ancestors, allies, or antagonists to grand systems of philosophy.Encompassing literature, philology, and philosophy, the history of the book and the history of reading, A Theory of the Aphorism invites us to reflect anew on what it means to think deeply about this pithiest of literary forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAdages.  aAnalects.  aAristotle.  aBlaise Pascal.  aCartesian philosophy.  aChina.  aChristian poetics.  aConfucius.  aDesiderius Erasmus.  aEuropean Renaissance.  aEuropean thinkers.  aFrancis Bacon.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aGospel of Thomas.  aHeraclitus.  aJesus.  aPensées.  aPlato.  aTwitter.  aanalog aphorism.  aancient proverbs.  aantiquity.  aaphorism.  aaphorisms.  aclassical culture.  aclickbaits.  acommentary.  acontinuous writing.  aconversations.  acultural network.  adiscursive philosophy.  afragment.  afragments.  aheadlines.  ahermeneutics.  ahuman intellect.  ainquiry.  aintelligible thought.  ainterpretation.  aliterary forms.  aliterary fragments.  alogos.  along-form publications.  amaxims.  amodernity.  anatural history.  aphilology.  aphilosophy.  aredemption.  asayings.  ascriptures.  aself-discovery.  asoteriology.  athought.  atwitterature.  averbal fragments.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110